@sdedic thanks for the review. I've added API methods for querying pseudo-keycodes for mouse events, and switched to them in other modules, including the existing editor zoom action.

I've kept away from introducing constants as we may in future need to consider changing the values used underneath.

One remaining use of magic constants of a sort is the names used in the UI.

@sroeper I have, although only with Rosetta.

However, have you changed any of the Maven settings from their defaults.  In particular, from https://github.com/apache/netbeans/issues/6181#issuecomment-1636480236 - do you have `Print Maven output logging level` enabled?

Can you share the output window contents from running the test?

@neilcsmith-net I am probably not involved enough to see the big picture. What happens if the build is done? Where does the mac.zip artefact come from? Is it build on a mac or just with a Clang compiler which has support for the arch arm64?

At least the build produced a universal binary with both architectures. So my assumption would be that we don't need the binaries for download anymore because they can be produced on the fly during the build. Is this wrong?

Sorry for asking this dump questions but I have not found any description of the build pipeline.

@sroeper the NetBeans IDE needs to be buildable on any OS, and the convenience binaries that ASF distributes are all based on the main binary zip built in a Linux Jenkins build - eg. https://ci-builds.apache.org/job/Netbeans/job/netbeans-TLP/job/release190/ .  Last time I checked, ASF didn't have macOS Jenkins at all anyway.

So, all native binaries need to be released separately then consumed in the build.  It's one of the added complexities that has led to these not being updated much in the past - eg. see problems updating in #2700 

There is a GitHub CI workflow here already for building the profiler binaries https://github.com/apache/netbeans/blob/master/.github/workflows/native-binary-build-lib.profiler.yml  We should probably extract to make releasing easier.

@sroeper I've opened a discussion on dev@ https://lists.apache.org/thread/08hsrfgn6klcf9bm8t96h6pv0zrysfjm

OSUOSL was intended for third-party binaries consumed in the build, such as the original Oracle CDDL licensed versions of the profiler binaries.  It should not really have been used for the later profiler binaries.  It's a legacy system we're meant to be moving away from.

We cannot use a fully automated process as we have to go through ASF release procedures.  Looking further I'm inclined to keep in this repo and adapt the GitHub workflow to include a source zip, and to release via dist.apache.org rather than Maven - but let's see what other people say.
